tags: aunt may just sorta adopts tony
summary: So, everyone is going on about how Tony looks out for Peter, but has anyone thought about Aunt May?
body:
So, everyone is going on about how Tony looks out for Peter, but has anyone thought about Aunt May?

Like, obviously they have to tell her Peter is… interning with Mr. Stark, and she would probably be so thrilled. Tony Stark sees the same potential in her boy that she does.

Being the wonderful person she is (and I will fight anyone who says otherwise), she would want to thank him in some way, because this is an amazing opportunity for Peter.

Now, just imagine that, offhandedly, Peter says he thinks one of the few things Mr. Stark doesn’t have is a handmade scarf. And she knits him one, like those Ironman ones you see at comic conventions and on Etsy.

Tony might not know how to react, because he is technically training this kid to fight crime, with some legit interning for him, mind you, and his aunt has made him a scraf?

It wouldn’t end with that, though. Tony drops Peter off at home? Oh, Mr. Stark, would you like to stay for dinner? She let’s him try a cookie she made for a bake sale, and he may or may not send someone to the sale to buy more. She asks him how he’s doing, she even talks with Pepper. She tells the school that, no, it’s okay if he goes with Mr. Stark after school, she’d be more worried about him if he took that many buses to get there.

When Peter falls, Tony is terrified of having to tell her if they can’t fix it, or going to tell her and finding she’s gone as well. But in the case of the former, he will look out for her for the rest of her days, even if she hates him.

So, yeah, Aunt May just decides to treat Tony as both a good influence on Peter and just part of the family and Tony puts her in the group of people he cares about.

Because Tony Stark may irritate me, but I won’t deny the man needs a makeshift family.
